description: From Osnaburg, the former English name of the German city of Osnabrück (from which it may have been first imported into English-speaking countries).

adjectives.description: osnaburg (comparative more osnaburg, superlative most osnaburg)

entries.meaning: (now chiefly US) Designating or made from this fabric. [from 17th c.]
(now chiefly US) A plain, coarse textile fabric made from flax, tow or jute yarns. [from 15th c.]
examples: [I]f he attended those solemn meetings at which the price of freight or the quality of Osnaburghs was discussed, he turned the venerable persons of the old merchants and grocers into ridicule  […] .
